ural History, Worldmaking, and Funeral Song in Hans Sloane’s Voyage to . . . Jamaica (1707–1725) -- tCrusoe’s Goat Umbrella -- tSpeaking in Voices: The South African Poetry of Thomas Pringle -- tBook Reviews -- tAndrew Pettegree and Arthur der Weduwen. The Bookshop of the World: Making and Trading Books in the Dutch Golden Age -- tW. R. Owens, Stuart Sim, and David Walker, eds. Bunyan Studies: A Journal of Reformation and Nonconformist Culture -- tMichael Edson, ed. Annotation in Eighteenth-Century Poetry -- tChristiane Hertel. Siting China in Germany: Eighteenth-Century Chinoiserie and Its Modern Legacy -- tBärbel Czennia and Greg Clingham, eds. Oriental Networks: Culture, Commerce and Communication in the Long Eighteenth Century -- tThomas F. Bonnell, ed. The Yale Editions of the Private Papers of James Boswell: Research Edition: James Boswell’s Life of Johnson: An Edition of the Original Manuscript in Four Volumes. Volume 4: 1780–1784 -- tPeter J. Aschenbrenner and Colin Lee, eds. The Papers of John Hatsell, Clerk of the House of Commons -- tDeborah Heller, ed. Bluestockings Now! The Evolution of a Social Role -- tEileen Hunt Botting. Mary Shelley and the Rights of the Child: Political Philosophy in Frankenstein -- tLee Jackson. Palaces of Pleasure: From Music Halls to the Seaside to Football, How the Victorians Invented Mass Entertainment -- tJohn M. Gingerich. Schubert’s Beethoven Project -- tEdina Adam and Julian Brooks, with an essay by Matthew Hargraves. William Blake: Visionary -- tFrances B. Singh. Scandal and Survival in Nineteenth-Century Scotland: The Life of Jane Cumming -- tAbout the Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRigorously inventive and revelatory in its adventurousness, 1650–1850 opens a forum for the discussion, investigation, and analysis of the full range of long-eighteenth-century writing, thinking, and artistry. Combining fresh considerations of prominent authors and artists with searches for overlooked or offbeat elements of the Enlightenment legacy, 1650–1850 delivers a comprehensive but richly detailed rendering of the first days, the first principles, and the first efforts of modern culture. Its pages open to the works of all nations and language traditions, providing a truly global picture of a period that routinely shattered boundaries. Volume 27 of this long-running journal is no exception to this tradition of focused inclusivity. Readers will travel through a blockbuster special feature on the topic of worldmaking and other worlds—on the Enlightenment zest for the discovery, charting, imagining, and evaluating of new worlds, envisioned worlds, utopian worlds, and worlds of the future. Essays in this enthusiastically extraterritorial offering escort readers through the science-fictional worlds of Lady Cavendish, around European gardens, over the high seas, across the American frontiers, into forests and exotic ecosystems, and, in sum, into the unlimited expanses of the Enlightenment mind. Further enlivening the volume is a cavalcade of full-length book reviews evaluating the latest in eighteenth-century scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAesthetics, Modern. 0aCivilization, Moderny18th centuryxHistory. 0aIdea (Philosophy)xHistory. 0aNineteenth century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aEnlightenment, Augustan, History of ideas, Aesthetics, Restoration.1 aBar-On Santor, Gefen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrett, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlack, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCahill, Samara Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCahill, Samara Anne,